f=Shared OS/logical/heath-made-to-stick.md · in=Chip Dan Heath's *Made Stick* (2007) definitive empirical framework ideas survive spread while others die. After decade research Chip Stanford studying naturally sticky ideas (urban legends, proverbs, conspiracy theories), Dan Thinkwell studying great teachers make complex topics memorable Heath brothers identified six shared traits across sticky idea they studied. They named framework **SUCCESs**: Simple, Unexpected, Concrete, Credible, Emotional, Stories. extraction operationalizes SUCCESs element definitions, psychological mechanisms, testable criteria, connections Brand Studio's foundational marketing laws (marketing_laws.py). core creative brief checklist spark's art-direction-critique gate lena's humanic-writing skill. · h2:PRINCIPLE 1 — SIMPLE=*Chapter 1, pp.25-72* · h3:Definition="Find core idea. Strip down critical essence. masters exclusion. relentlessly prioritize." (Ch.1, p.28) Simple mean "dumbed down" "sound bites." ideal simplicity **proverb** compact statement simple profound. Golden Rule ("Do unto others you them unto you") ultimate simple idea: one sentence deep individual spend lifetime learning follow it. · h3:Mechanism: Commander's Intent=*Ch.1, pp.34-40* Heaths borrow military concept **Commander's Intent** (CI) U.S. Army's planning process. crisp, plain-talk statement appears top order, specifying plan's goal, desired end-state operation." answers: "If nothing else tomorrow, accomplish _________." single important thing. plan survives contact enemy, clear Commander's Intent allows soldiers ground improvise adaptively toward shared goal. Heaths (Ch.1, p.40): "Commander's Intent manages align behavior soldiers levels without requiring play-by-play instructions their leaders. people know desired destination, they're free improvise needed." **Civilian examples book (Ch.1, pp.41-52):** · h3:Mechanism: Commander's Intent=**Southwest Airlines:** "THE low-fare airline." decision peanut policy fleet selection route planning judged against single core. (Ch.1, pp.41-46), **JFK's moon speech (1961):** "Put man moon return him safely end decade." Contrast "CEO version": "Our mission become international leader space industry through maximum team-centered innovation strategically targeted aerospace initiatives." (Introduction, pp.24-25) · h3:Simple Test (from Ch.1)=core idea expressed single sentence frontline employee remember Monday morning? guide decisions? (If it's equally consistent two opposite choices, it's core it's platitude.) passed down through organization like proverb refined, distorted, retelling? Commander's Intent mission statement? (Intent guides action; mission statements decorate walls.) · h3:Connection to marketing_laws.py=\| Heath (Simple) \| marketing_laws.py \| Mechanism \| · h3:Connection to marketing_laws.py=\|---------------\|-------------------\|-----------\| · h3:Connection to marketing_laws.py=\| "Find the core" \| **Hick's Law** (hicks_law) — fewer choices = faster decisions. A simple core reduces cognitive load. A message with 1 core point embeds faster than one with 10. \| Hick (1952): RT = a + b * log2(n+1). 3 options = fast; 7 = slow; 20+ = paralysis. \| · h3:Connection to marketing_laws.py=\| "Masters of exclusion" \| **Law of Focus** (law_of_focus) — Ries & Trout, Ch.5: Own ONE word in the prospect's mind. You cannot own "safety" AND "luxury" AND "performance." \| Exclusion is the mechanism of focus. Southwest owns "low-fare" — they cannot also own "luxury." \| · h3:Connection to marketing_laws.py=\| "Proverbs, not sound bites" \| **Mere Exposure Effect** (mere_exposure_effect) — repeated exposures build liking. Proverbs survive centuries because they compress wisdom into a form that survives retelling. \| The compact form enables repetition. \| · h2:PRINCIPLE 3 — CONCRETE=*Chapter 3, pp.109-143* · h3:Definition="We explain our ideas terms human actions, terms sensory information. Speaking concretely way ensure our idea mean thing everyone our audience." (Ch.3, p.109) Concrete means: specific people doing specific things, abstract nouns doing abstract verbs. "Maximize shareholder value" (abstract) vs. "THE low-fare airline" (concrete). "Deliver best-in-class customer experience" (abstract) vs. "The Ritz-Carlton credo: ladies gentlemen serving ladies gentlemen" (concrete). · h3:Mechanism: Velcro Theory Memory=*Ch.3, pp.116-125* "Concrete ideas like Velcro they lots hooks grab onto your memory. Abstract ideas like Teflon nothing sticks." (Ch.3, pp.116-117) Heaths explain: "Concreteness creates shared understanding. Boeing engineer speaks pod prove difficult average airline mechanic open,' concrete. consultant speaks 'synergistic cross-platform optimization,' abstract meaningless. engineer's statement means exactly thing listener. consultant's statement means nothing anyone, including consultant." (Ch.3, pp.118-119) Velcro metaphor: concrete sensory detail color, sound, texture, human action "hook loop" memory. hooks, surfaces idea cling to. Abstract ideas smooth Teflon hooks. **The "fox grapes" test (Ch.3, pp.124-127):** "Aesop's fables survived 2,500 years because they encode abstract moral truths concrete stories. 'Don't sore loser' abstract forgettable. 'The fox, unable reach grapes, walked away muttering they probably sour anyway' concrete, visual, unforgettable." moral embedded sensory experience. · h3:The Abstract-to-Concrete Translation=*Ch.3, pp.130-138* Heaths provide translation exercise: · h3:The Abstract-to-Concrete Translation=Abstract: "We improve knowledge management across enterprise.", Concrete: "We need way engineer Tulsa learn engineer Singapore's mistake." · h3:The Abstract-to-Concrete Translation=key question: "What look like practice? What see, hear, feel?" you cannot answer this, idea concrete. **Rule lena's humanic-writing:** sentence creative brief survive concrete test. claim doesn't evoke sensory action-oriented image, re-write it. · h3:Concrete Test (from Ch.3)=**Sensory check:** idea evoke specific image, sound, physical sensation? **Velcro check:** many "memory hooks" present? (Count them: specific people, places, objects, actions, sensory details.) **Shared meaning check:** different people, reading independently, form mental picture? **Translation check:** you act out idea? you "did" idea short skit, what audience see? · h3:Connection to marketing_laws.py=\| Heath (Concrete) \| marketing_laws.py \| Mechanism \| · h3:Connection to marketing_laws.py=\|-----------------\|-------------------\|-----------\| · h3:Connection to marketing_laws.py=\| "Sensory hooks" \| **Von Restorff Effect** — concrete details create distinctiveness. A table full of greasy food is more memorable than "37g saturated fat." \| Concrete = distinctive = memorable. \| · h3:Connection to marketing_laws.py=\| "Shared meaning" \| **Lasswell Model** (lasswell_model) — the message element must be unambiguous. "What does it mean?" must have ONE answer. \| Lasswell (1948): A complete communication requires a clear message. Concrete ensures clarity. \| · h3:Connection to marketing_laws.py=\| "Velcro Theory" \| **Mere Exposure Effect** — concrete ideas survive repeated exposure without boredom (they have enough hooks to be re-experienced). \| Abstract ideas become grating on repetition; concrete ones reveal new facets. \| · h2:PRINCIPLE 5 — EMOTIONAL=*Chapter 5, pp.176-208* · h3:Definition="How get people care about our ideas? make them feel something. Research shows people likely make charitable gift single needy individual entire impoverished region. wired feel things people, abstractions." (Ch.5, p.176) · h3:Mechanism Mother Teresa Effect=*Ch.5, pp.180-186* Heaths cite research Paul Slovic (University Oregon, cited Ch.5, pp.180-181): people shown photo starving seven-year-old girl named Rokia Mali, they gave generously. people shown statistics about starvation affecting million children Malawi, donations dropped significantly. given Rokia's story statistics, donations dropped near "statistics only" level. statistics actually DEADENED emotional response. Heaths (Ch.5, p.183): "The Mother Teresa effect 'If look mass, never act. look one, will.' empirical finding human empathy scales DOWN individuals, statistics. help one see feel, millions count." **Application marketing/communication (Ch.5, pp.184-186):** "If you want people care about cause, product, idea show them ONE person affected. show them aggregate. aggregate numbs. individual activates." · h3:Mechanism Semantic Stretch "Emotion"=*Ch.5, pp.188-195* Heaths distinguish between two kinds emotional appeal: **"Hitting people gut"** fear, disgust, anger, awe. knee-jerk response. movie popcorn campaign triggered disgust food table visual. **"Appealing self-interest"** what's THEM? WIIFY ("What's You?") framework. **The WIIFY framework (Ch.5, pp.191-195):** People care about ideas affect them personally. Telling teenager about 400,000 annual smoking deaths abstract. Showing them Big Tobacco manipulated them specifically "They knew lied you" personal. Heaths (Ch.5, p.193): "WIIFY doesn't mean 'make everything selfish.' means 'make consequences tangible specific human you're talking to.' consequences merger abstract line worker unless you explain affects their department, their role, their paycheck." · h3:Mechanism Power Identity Appeals=*Ch.5, pp.196-204* Heaths cite famous "Don't Mess Texas" anti-littering campaign (Ch.5, pp.196-199): "The campaign didn't appeal environmental consciousness civic duty abstract concepts weak emotional pull. appealed TEXAS PRIDE deeply felt identity. Littering wasn't 'bad environment'; insult Texas." emotional lever "litter wrong" "you Texan, Texans don't trash their state." identity-based emotional appeal, far powerful values-based one. **Identity vs. values table (Ch.5, pp.200-204):** · h3:Mechanism Power Identity Appeals=\| Appeal Type \| Example \| Emotional Strength \| Duration \| · h3:Mechanism Power Identity Appeals=\|-------------\|---------\|-------------------\|----------\| · h3:Mechanism Power Identity Appeals=\| **Values** (abstract) \| "Protect the environment" \| Weak — applies to everyone, activates no one \| Fades quickly \| · h3:Mechanism Power Identity Appeals=\| **Identity** (specific) \| "Don't mess with Texas" \| Strong — applies to Texans specifically \| Endures for years \| · h3:Mechanism Power Identity Appeals=\| **Self-interest** (individual) \| "This will save you $200/year" \| Medium-strong — activates personal benefit \| Lasts until benefit is achieved \| · h3:Mechanism Power Identity Appeals=\| **Group identity** (tribal) \| "Real programmers use Vim" \| Very strong — activates belonging/threat \| Endures as long as identity is salient \| · h3:Emotional Test (from Ch.5)=**The ONE test:** you showing audience one individual they feel for, mass statistics? **The WIIFY test:** audience know exactly what's THEM personally, concretely? **The identity test:** message tap specific identity audience holds (Texan, parent, professional, athlete)? **The arousal test:** message trigger high-arousal emotion (awe, excitement, anger, fear) low-arousal (sadness, contentment)? High arousal action. Low arousal passivity. (Cross-reference: Berger's Emotion chapter berger-contagious.md.) · h3:Connection to marketing_laws.py=\| Heath (Emotional) \| marketing_laws.py \| Mechanism \| · h3:Connection to marketing_laws.py=\|------------------\|-------------------\|-----------\| · h3:Connection to marketing_laws.py=\| "Mother Teresa — the ONE vs. the many" \| **Cialdini's Liking** (cialdini_liking) — similarity to an individual triggers identification. We like the one we can relate to. \| Cialdini (1984), Ch.5: "We prefer to say yes to people we know and like." A named individual triggers liking; "3 million children" does not. \| · h3:Connection to marketing_laws.py=\| "Identity appeals" \| **Cialdini's Commitment/Consistency** — identity pledges create internal consistency pressure. "I am a Texan → Texans don't litter → I don't litter." \| The self-image consistency drive (Cialdini, Ch.3) is the mechanism that makes identity appeals durable. \| · h3:Connection to marketing_laws.py=\| "WIIFY — personal benefit" \| **Kotler's 4 Ps** (kotler_4p) — the "Promotion" P must communicate benefits, not features. WIIFY = the benefit of the Promotion translated to the receiver. \| Kotler (1967): Features tell; benefits sell. WIIFY is the emotional translation of features → personal benefits. \| · h2:THE COMPLETE SUCCESs CHECKLIST=*Epilogue, pp.245-260; "Making Ideas Stick: Easy Reference Guide," pp.261-270* master checklist reproduced Heaths' epilogue reference guide. creative brief Brand Studio scored against list. · h3:Simple: Find Core=What Commander's Intent? single important thing nothing else survives, must. compact? employee remember Monday morning? profound? Short easy. Short deep goal. Proverbs, sound bites. guide decisions? supports two contradictory choices, it's core. **Ogilvy alignment:** Ogilvy's Big Idea test ("Could used years?") simplicity test. Big Idea Commander's Intent. · h3:Unexpected: Violate Expectations=What schema you violating? violation produce genuine surprise (not confusion)? What gap you opening? personal audience? you fill gap? Surprise without resolution betrayal. **Ogilvy alignment:** Ogilvy's "Did make you gasp?" Big Idea criterion surprise test. · h3:Concrete: Make Sensory=you see, hear, touch idea? many sensory hooks have? people form mental picture? acted out? Abstract ideas cannot performed. **Ogilvy alignment:** Ogilvy's Specificity Principle ("specific facts stick") concreteness. · h3:Credible: Help People Test=Sinatra Test single extreme example proves point? testable credentials audience verify using their experience? details vivid true? statistics made human-scale relatable? **Ogilvy alignment:** Ogilvy's Research-Before-Creativity Rule research-backed claims credible claims. · h3:Emotional: Make People Care=you showing ONE person, mass statistic? (Mother Teresa effect) What identity you appealing to? clear WIIFY? What's specific person? emotion high-arousal (awe, excitement, anger, fear)? **Ogilvy alignment:** Ogilvy's Rule (Consumer-Is-Your-Wife) emotional respect rule. "She's moron she's someone you care about." · h3:Stories: Drive Action Through Simulation=What story archetype fit? (Challenge, Connection, Creativity) audience mentally rehearse desired behavior? customers tell story their words? (Shop Talk test) brand story, glued story? (Trojan Horse test) **Ogilvy alignment:** Ogilvy's "Big Idea" stories Hathaway man eye patch, Rolls-Royce clock, Schweppes Commander Whitehead enduring SUCCESs stories. · h3:SUCCESs + STEPPS (Berger)=\| Heath (SUCCESs) \| Berger (STEPPS) \| Integration \| · h3:SUCCESs + STEPPS (Berger)=\|----------------\|-----------------\|-------------\| · h3:SUCCESs + STEPPS (Berger)=\| Simple \| Practical Value (Ch.5) \| Simple ideas with practical utility = maximum shareability \| · h3:SUCCESs + STEPPS (Berger)=\| Unexpected \| Social Currency (Ch.1) \| Unexpected things make the sharer look smart/in-the-know \| · h3:SUCCESs + STEPPS (Berger)=\| Concrete \| Stories (Ch.6) \| Concrete details make stories transportable \| · h3:SUCCESs + STEPPS (Berger)=\| Credible \| Triggers (Ch.2) \| Repeated credible messages build top-of-mind association \| · h3:SUCCESs + STEPPS (Berger)=\| Emotional \| Emotion (Ch.3) \| Direct mapping — high-arousal = shared, low-arousal = not \| · h3:SUCCESs + STEPPS (Berger)=\| Stories \| Stories + Public (Ch.4, Ch.6) \| Stories leave a "public residue" on the sharer \| · h3:SUCCESs + Ogilvy=Ogilvy rule maps onto SUCCESs: · h3:SUCCESs + Ogilvy=Consumer-Is-Your-Wife Emotional Credible, Big Idea Simple (Commander's Intent), Specificity = Concrete, Research-Backed = Credible, Headline Rule Simple Emotional, Brand Image Emotional Stories · h3:SUCCESs Ries Trout=Law Focus Simple (own ONE word; Commander's Intent), Law Leadership Credible (first mind), Law Perception Unexpected (perception gap schema violation)